english:
  title: Record of Choe Seungje's Ten-Character Pavilion
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: 'Administrator Choe, a man of rank and standing, erected a pavilion to the west of his residence—a marvel indeed, something the world had never before witnessed. In the ordinary construction of buildings, one lays beams horizontally and ridgepoles lengthwise, sets short pillars upon beams and arranges rafters in their grooves. Such is the common way. Yet this pavilion—its four corners form the shape of the Chinese character for ten, while its interior opens square like a well. It resembles what the world calls a tent-hall, and thus takes the name "Ten-Character." Within this square void, mirrors fill every space. Light cascades and illuminates, penetrating within and without. Every figure of man and thing—whether thick or thin, great or small—appears transformed in each moment, all poured into this luminous chamber. To gaze upward strikes one with awe. The flying eaves, curved brackets and layered beams seem to soar outward, like branches splayed and angled, some like dragons ascending, others like phoenixes in flight. Each peculiar form and strange construction differs from the rest, each presenting its own wonder. Even the mathematician Lishou, calculating all, would set down his counting-rods in bewilderment, unable to reckon their number. The scarlet lacquer, red and green pigments, carved and colored ornaments gleam resplendent—aurora-striped, cloud-wreathed—now like moonlight''s flowing radiance, now like scattered stars adorned in brilliance. Even one with eyes as keen as Lilu would be dazzled, pupils overwhelmed, not daring to raise his gaze. Whether such designs exist in the Wood Classic itself, I cannot say. In antiquity too, there were great families and noble clans whose wealth reached heaven itself—yet fine timber and wondrous wood were not born only in this age and absent from the past. Skilled craftsmen and artisans like the legendary Banzhui have appeared in every generation. How then had we never heard from ancient times of pavilions and pleasure halls so wondrous as this, only now to behold them for the first time? Is it not that the Administrator''s vision and architectural wisdom have surpassed what the ancients achieved? Though lords and ministers of this world might attempt to replicate such a structure, they could not come remotely close. Even if they could build it, preserving it would prove far more difficult. Why? Their deeds have not accumulated in the royal court, their grace has not spread to the common people—should such splendor suddenly arise beyond their station, it would become only a burden upon themselves. How then could it endure? Yet Administrator Choe was born into a house of accumulated virtue, commands the regard of the entire court, and his achievements in devising strategy and bringing peace to the realm shine forth, vying with sun and moon for brightness. His hidden benevolence and manifest virtue have seeped deep into people''s very flesh. Thus heaven and earth, gods and spirits themselves support him. What hardship could touch him? What place could he not preserve? Recently the Administrator summoned me and said: "You have seen this pavilion, yet you do not know its pleasures. When gentle winds blow and peach and apricot blossoms burst forth together, I sit with those who wear cicadas in their ears and turtle-shells at their waist, offering courtesies and yielding precedence to one another upon dragon-whisker grass mats. Round tables display their finest arrangements; golden goblets flutter like birds. The supreme beauties of Eastern Wu and lovely maidens of the Southern kingdoms play the zither—clear springs seem to leap forth; they sing, and floating clouds come to rest. Fragrant winds and orchid essence scatter fifty miles around, rivaling the flowers and willows in their bloom. This is what I have gained from spring. When summer''s fire rages with fierce heat, I open the northern windows wide; cool breezes sweep through. The deep pavilion casts its own shadow; sunlight cannot peer within. I surround myself with cold ice, fan it with great fans, and furnish it with green pines and emerald cypresses, which offer fair shade and send forth clear sounds. The air becomes chill and crisp as autumn''s eighth or ninth moon—one forgets that the world outside burns with stone-melting, metal-fusing flame. This is what I have gained from summer. In autumn and winter, I have warm chambers and heated halls. The pavilion offers me such pleasure, yet I have nothing with which to repay it. I only wish to inscribe it with fine and flourished words, making them the pavilion''s glory. Can you undertake this?" I demurred, but could not refuse. Thus I spoke to the Administrator: "This is truly, sir, the pleasure you have found. Yet you have spoken only of what lies without. What dwells within your heart is vast and boundless as rivers and seas without end, broad and infinite as heaven and earth itself—untouched by age of sun and moon, unseen by spirits and ghosts. It is not something one such as I could measure or capture in writing. Yet your command is stern, and I dare not refuse to recount at least its outlines, responding to what you have found in the external world. As for what you have inwardly gained—that must await a master of letters to unfold its purity and render it complete. How could I presume to such a task?" So records Lee, of the Hanlin Academy.'
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Lishou (隸首): An ancient figure legendary for his mathematical prowess, used here to emphasize the incomprehensible complexity of the pavilion''s structure.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Lilu (離婁): An ancient sage renowned for his extraordinary eyesight; evoked to emphasize the pavilion''s dazzling beauty.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Eastern Wu and Southern kingdoms: References to ancient Chinese regions and their celebrated beauties, used to evoke romance and refinement.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Dragon-whisker grass: A precious type of grass used for fine mats and furnishings in aristocratic settings.'
